    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Yeah, that \"any and all\" part is definitely scary. It feels like there's a lot of room for them to dig up stuff later and hit me with unexpected costs. Are there certain ways people try to sneak in more liability that aren't immediately obvious?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, some clauses can be sneaky, like the \"indemnification\" clause itself. Another common tactic is to use \"catch-all\" language, like \"including but not limited to\" or \"without limitation.\" These phrases can be used to expand the scope of the clause, making it harder to understand what's actually covered. It's also worth keeping an eye out for clauses that reference \"third-party beneficiaries\" or \"successors and assigns,\" as these can sometimes create new liabilities for you. It's a good idea to have a lawyer review the contract carefully to help you spot any potential traps.",
